<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Disruption feared over security cordon around City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, JIMMY BURNS and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECURITY cordon set up around the City of London at the weekend faces
its first test today amid fears that it could cause widespread traffic
congestion.
The anti-terrorist scheme, which rings London's financial heart with 24-hour
police checkpoints, has received broad support from business, which pressed
for tighter security after the Bishopsgate bomb attack by the Provisional
IRA two months ago.
But with 18 roads leading into the Square Mile being closed under the
scheme, police and City leaders were preparing for a barrage of complaints
from frustrated motorists.
The City of London Police, stressing that the scheme was experimental,
appealed to commuters to leave their cars at home. 'For the first days there
will be problems. It would be naive of us to expect otherwise,' the police
said.
The RAC, the motoring organisation, said it was unhappy about the City being
treated in isolation. 'The scheme could transfer the traffic, and
potentially, the terrorists to other areas,' it warned.
The Corporation of London, which is funding the Pounds 200,000 scheme,
expects 3,000 cars an hour will be displaced to other parts of London by the
security scheme, while a further 5,000 an hour try to pass through the City
during the first few days.
The scheme is planned to operate for 12 months, pending a public inquiry
into further security measures.
Bus drivers have been issued with instructions about route diversions -
although a helpline operator said many were still struggling to make sense
of the new maps.
Mr Michael Cassidy, chairman of the Corporation of London's policy
committee, admitted that while the scheme would give better protection
against the threat of car bombs, it could not guard against hand-held
devices.
RAC warns of 'nightmare', Page 6
</TEXT>
