<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Bank code faces big shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE committee reviewing the code of practice for banks and building
societies is to consider changing it. The aim would be to ensure that
societies inform investors more clearly of alterations in the level of
interest paid on different accounts.
The lack of clear notification to investors that their accounts offer lower
returns than newer products from the same society has become one of the main
sources of complaint by customers.
The review committee, set up by clearing banks to discuss changes to the
code from next March, is also likely to consider stronger requirements for
banks to obtain the free consent of customers before disclosing account data
internally.
Some banks including Barclays have been criticised for requiring customers
to sign clauses consenting to their account details being given to the
bank's sales subsidiaries.
Sir George Blunden, a former deputy governor of the Bank of England who is
heading the review committee, said that he could not prejudge the outcome of
discussions, but it was already clear that several aspects of the code would
have to be examined over the next few months.
Sir George said that initial submissions from interested parties, including
consumer groups, had raised a number of concerns. The National Association
of Citizens Advice Bureaux last week said that the voluntary code was being
ignored by many banks.
The committee is reviewing how the voluntary code, signed by the British
Bankers Association and the Building Societies Association, has worked since
its introduction in March 1992. It was intended as an alternative to legal
regulation.
The committee's work is backed by banks and societies but some officials
believe there could be conflict between the committee and financial services
companies if its recommendations proved onerous.
Other revisions to the code which the committee is likely to consider
include:
Banks having to give stronger warnings to business partners - particularly
the spouses of small business owners - of the unlimited liability they could
incur by giving personal guarantees to underwrite business loans.
Banks being required to 'pre-notify' charges to be deducted from customers'
current accounts, rather than simply publishing account tariffs. National
Westminster introduced such a policy this year.
Banks and societies being barred from imposing 'interest on charges' in
cases where charges on accounts put customers into overdraft and so attract
interest payments. Banks are already barred from making account charges in
such cases.
Although banks and societies might resist changes which will cost them large
sums to implement or disrupt attempts to sell more products to their
customers, the committee will be under some pressure to respond to public
opinion.
The National Association of Citizens Advice Bureaux last week published its
submission to the review committee, which called for banks to observe a
statutory code of practice. It said they were ignoring the spirit of the
voluntary one.
</TEXT>
