</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER 100,000 con-struction jobs are expected to be lost this year and
next, taking the total number of jobs shed since 1989 to almost 500,000,
says a forecast published today by the Royal Institution of Chartered
Surveyors, Andrew Taylor writes.
Over-capacity in the industry means jobs are likely to continue to be lost
even though construction output is predicted to recover by 3.6 per cent next
year.
The forecast used a computer-based model for the construction industry
developed by Reading University, Cambridge Econometrics and quantity
surveyors Gardiner &amp; Theobald.
