<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Willis questions pit reprieves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS MANY as six of the 12 pits reprieved by the government's coal white paper
are soon to close, Mr Norman Willis, general-secretary of the Trades Union
Congress, said yesterday.
On the eve of today's Commons debate on coal Mr Willis used a letter to Mr
John Major to accuse the government of failing to address 'the fundamental
issues of the market' and to predict that over the next 18 months 38 pits
would close.
The letter came as National Power, the largest electricity generator,
confirmed that it would not consider additional coal purchases until the
autumn.
British Coal has already negotiated to sell 40m tonnes of coal to the main
electricity generators this year but needs to increase sales by a further
15m tonnes a year if the future of the 12 pits is to be secured.
In today's debate on a Labour motion urging the government to adopt
recommendations put forward by a cross-party committee of MPs in January, Mr
Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, is expected to renew his
recent attack on the coal white paper as a 'fraud'.
At least one Conservative MP has served notice of an intention to vote
against the government or to abstain.
Labour's motion criticises the government for encouraging the belief that
its white paper would reprieve 12 pits and widen the market for their coal
by providing a subsidy for their output. It notes that 'within three months
of its publication two of those pits have already closed'.
The confirmation of National Power's position on additional coal purchases
came in a memorandum sent last week to Mrs Elizabeth Peacock, the
Conservative MP for Batley &amp; Spen, a prominent coal rebel.
The company said it had 'no commercial need' for further coal at present and
would in any case have nowhere to put the additional supplies.
It said it had nearly 20m tonnes of coal at power station sites and
additional supplies would not be burnt for 'some considerable time'.
It said it would 'reconsider the question of possible additional purchases
in the autumn'.
</TEXT>
