<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Executive pay rises slow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK EXECUTIVES' pay rises have slowed to less than half the annual rate that
prevailed at the start of the recession, the latest index produced for the
Financial Times by the Noble Lowndes group of management consultancies
shows.
The index, which includes benefits such as cars and pensions as well as
salaries and bonuses, shows an average increase for all ranks of executives
of 5.3 per cent over the past 12 months. The figure for just the first six
months of 1990 was 6.5 per cent.
As companies have put a tight grip on pay expenditure, the average annual
rate of increase even for chief executives has fallen below 6 per cent. Yet
there are signs that, after applying the brake increasingly hard to last
December, companies are starting to relax it again.
Noble Lowndes, PO Box 144, Norfolk House, Wellesley Road, Croydon CR9 3EB.
</TEXT>
