<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Fears over redundancy still rising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff and DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PERCENTAGE of workers who fear they could lose their jobs within the
next 12 months continues to rise, in spite of the fourth consecutive drop in
official unemployment figures, a MORI survey published exclusively in the
Financial Times reveals today.
The increasing fear of redundancy is particularly pronounced among women,
people aged 18 to 34 and those living in the Midlands.
A quarter of those in work say they are 'very concerned' about being made
redundant, rising to 36 per cent among the youngest category, 18- to
24-year-olds.
The survey appears to indicate that some confidence has returned during the
past month to professional and managerial employees.
But overall, 44 per cent of workers are now 'very' or 'fairly' worried they
could be made redundant over the coming year - up from 41 per cent in April,
the first month of the research series, commissioned from MORI by Industrial
Relations Services, the independent pay and conditions research group.
Official seasonally-adjusted unemployment figures fell between April and May
by 26,100 to 2.914m. This fourth consecutive monthly fall cut the
seasonally-adjusted jobless rate to 10.4 per cent from 10.5 per cent in
April and a winter peak of 10.6 per cent.
Mr Andrew Brode, IRS publisher, said the continued rise in the IRS/MORI
index 'shows that in the real world - uninhabited by politicians - all is
not well'.
Anxiety among women has risen 5 percentage points since April to 40 per
cent, but is still lower than the fear shown by men that they could lose
their jobs: 46 per cent of men were worried in April, a figure which rose
slightly to 47 per cent by June.
Concern among 18- to 34-year-olds has risen from 40 per cent to 48 per cent
since April and, among all groups of employees in the Midlands, from 40 per
cent to 49 per cent. May saw a sharp increase in fear of redundancy among
social groups A and B - 28 per cent in April to 41 per cent - but this has
now dropped back down to 32 per cent.
MORI interviewed 978 adults aged 18 and over in full-time or part-time work,
face-to-face in their homes, across 147 constituency sampling points
throughout Britain on June 24-28. Data was weighted to match the profile of
the population.
The Finance and Leasing Association says in a report today that consumer
credit in May was 29 per cent higher than a year earlier, Daniel Green
writes. Motor finance was up 16 per cent and finance for the business
community rose a 'patchy' 15 per cent.
New car loans are leading the way in a recovery in consumer demand according
to a report today from Infolink, the credit information organisation.
</TEXT>
