<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Professor Gerald Curtis offers opinions on Japanese
political funding reform
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Gerald Curtis, probably the foremost western commentator on
Japanese politics, offers this judgment about how Japanese politicians
responded to the 1975 reform of political funding: 'Japanese politicians
rose to the challenge posed by these reforms by searching out every
conceivable loophole in the law that might allow them to avoid having to
change their time-tried ways of doing things.
'The reforms offered eloquent testimony to the difficulty of engineering
political change in a society that has resilient political institutions and
traditions.
'They demonstrated not only that the consequences of reform cannot be
entirely anticipated, but that they often exacerbate the problems they are
intended to correct and create others that are worse.'
</TEXT>
