<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / German minister quits over shootout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Rudolf Seiters, Germany's federal interior minister, yesterday resigned
after coming under mounting pressure from the media and politicians for his
handling of a shootout between German police and suspected left-wing
terrorists.
The resignation brings to 20 the number of ministers who have quit
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's governments since he came to power in 1982.
Six ministers have resigned since the beginning of the year, highlighting
the internal problems the centre-right coalition faces as it prepares for
re-election next year.
The government's public image recently suffered a setback when Mr Theo
Waigel, the federal finance minister, announced his willingness to leave the
cabinet if he was chosen to replace former Bavarian premier Max Streibl.
Mr Seiters and Mr Alexander von Stahl, the federal prosecutor, have been
under attack for not disclosing the exact circumstances under which Mr
Wolfgang Grams, a suspected member of the Red Army Faction, died last
Sunday.
Mr Seiters said he was taking personal responsibility for the 'mistakes, the
lack of clarity and of co-ordination in the police'.
Reports in the German media, based on the accounts of witnesses, allege that
police shot Mr Grams at point-blank range when he was on the floor and
unarmed.
Der Spiegel, the German weekly magazine, quoted a police officer as saying
that 'the killing was like an execution'.
Earlier in the week the Interior Ministry had said Mr Grams had been shot at
from a distance of 1.5 metres. It had called the arrest a model of
anti-terrorist action.
The German media have also questioned whether Mr Michael Newrzella, an
anti-terrorist police officer who died in the shootout, was killed by the
suspected terrorist or by a colleague. Mr Gerhard Kohler, vice-president of
the federal criminal office, yesterday denied he was killed by police.
Mr Seiters, a Christian Democrat, has been in the spotlight recently because
of his role in trying to contain violence against foreigners. He was also
instrumental in pushing through the legislative amendment which has
toughened the country's previously liberal asylum law.
</TEXT>
