<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Defendants face abolition of right to elect trial by jury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ABOLITION of a def-endant's right to elect trial by jury will be
recommended tomorrow in a report by the Royal Commission on Criminal
Justice.
At the moment, defendants are allowed to choose jury trial in cases which
can be tried either by magistrates or in a crown court.
Sources within the Criminal Bar who have seen the commission's report said
the commission had been convinced that allowing defendants to elect jury
trial only to have them plead guilty at the crown court was a waste of court
time and resources.
According to one QC this proposal will cause a political storm. Mrs Barbara
Mills QC, the director of public prosecutions, has been pushing for the
change. But Lord Taylor, the lord chief justice, is strongly opposed,
describing the right to jury trial as 'an inalienable right stretching back
to the Magna Carta'.
The commission, chaired by Lord Runciman, will also recommend that
defendants must disclose their defence before trial once the case against
them has been outlined by the prosecution. The commission makes a number of
suggestions as to how such an obligation might be enforced, and appears to
favour holding defendants who refuse to co-operate in contempt with the
ultimate sanction of being jailed.
These measures are seen by criminal barristers as the most controversial
proposals in the report.
'I think it is a reasonably solid report,' said one QC, 'not very exciting -
it's not revamping anything. But that's not a bad thing. It would be fatal
to go for too radical change when the system works well in general.'
The commission, which was set up in March 1991 after a series of
miscarriages of justice had rocked public confidence in the criminal justice
system, has stopped short of recommending abolition of the so-called right
to silence of the accused.
Although it will recommend that defendants should disclose their case, and
that juries should be able to draw inferences from the defendant's silence
at trial, it says that the accused should not lose the right to stay silent
at the police station.
The Runciman report also concludes that there is no need for a requirement
that confession evidence should be corroborated before it can be admissable
as evidence at trial. Instead, the commission will recommend that judges
should give a warning to juries about placing too much emphasis on a
confession which is unsupported by other evidence. Similar warnings are
already given to juries about identification evidence.
Among the other recommendations, the commission calls for:
An independent tribunal to investigate alleged miscarriages of justice and
refer cases back to the Appeal Court;
A system of sentence discounts, where judges will outline a maximum sentence
a defendant would receive if he pleaded guilty;
An independent forensic science service available to both defence and
prosecution.
</TEXT>
