<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 93 / Smith heads for confrontation over unions' block vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH has set himself on a collision course with the trade unions at
this autumn's Labour conference by refusing to moderate plans to reduce
their collective role in the party's decision-making.
In an interview with the Financial Times, the Labour leader underlined his
determination to ensure that union participation in the selection of the
party's parliamentary candidates could be exercised only through the
individual party membership of trade unionists.
This one-member, one-vote principle has already been rejected by a majority
of trade unions. The TGWU, the largest union affiliated to the party, will
this week join others in insisting that, as Labour's paymasters, they must
retain a collective voice in the choice of candidates.
But Mr Smith said: 'I did not become leader of the Labour party just to do
easy things. I have the responsibility as leader to do what I think is
right. And I will do it. It's my job to seek to persuade people.' He added:
'I am under no illusions that it's an easy battle to win but I am determined
to win it.'
Despite the threat of a humiliating defeat at the party conference, where
the unions hold 70 per cent of the votes, Mr Smith insisted a decision could
not be deferred for a further year: 'I will fight on . . . I hope I will
succeed in persuading people to adopt it at the conference.'
Mr Smith rejected a compromise floated by some unions which would give votes
only to those trade unionists who paid the political levy to their unions
and were willing to sign a register of Labour supporters. Instead he wants
individual trade unionists to join the party.
'We have got to have people who choose to be members of the party,' he said.
He agreed this would mean that they would have to pay another fee in
addition to the political levy (an average of Pounds 1.70 per person).
The incentives for trade unionists to join the party directly would include
a significant cut in the Pounds 18 annual party membership fee. Stressing
the need for greater democracy, he added: 'It is not just one-member one
vote. It is a lot more members and a lot more votes.'
Mr Smith predicted his plan would have strong support from the constituency
delegations at the conference. But with those delegations accounting for
only 30 per cent of the vote, he is relying on a last-minute retreat by the
unions, and on inter-union divisions, to avoid a damaging defeat.
Mr Smith was keeping open the possibility of a compromise in his separate
dispute with the unions over their role in the election of the party leader.
He was ready to consider the possibility that the unions' representation in
the electoral college, which chooses the leader, could be calculated on the
basis of the unions' proposed register of Labour supporters.
David Goodhart writes: Mr Bill Morris, leader of the TGWU party, yesterday
strongly reaffirmed the union's hostility to Mr Smith's reforms.
He said there was 'absolutely no need' to change the current constitutional
relationship and the debate was just a 'distraction'. But he suggested a new
argument for delaying the decision for one year if Boundaries Commission
changes enable parliamentary selections to be deferred.
The union is unlikely to regard Mr Smith's clarification of his position on
electing the party leader as an important concession. One official said last
night: 'We care much more about the selection of candidates, we have always
been involved in that.'
By-election pressure, Page 7
John Smith interview, Page 13
</TEXT>
<XX>
