<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 93 / US ends opposition to Vietnam loan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US is to drop its opposition to a multilateral plan to clear Vietnam's
arrears to the International Monetary Fund, paving the way for the Hanoi
government's reinstatement in the international financial system, President
Bill Clinton said yesterday.
But Mr Clinton said progress so far on resolving questions about US
servicemen taken as prisoners of war or listed as missing in action during
the Vietnam war was 'simply not sufficient' to justify lifting the US trade
embargo.
Yesterday's announcement will allow a group of countries led by France to
move ahead with a plan to lend Vietnam the money it needs to pay off its
Dollars 140m (Pounds 93.3m) arrears to the IMF. This would in turn open the
way for Vietnam to negotiate more substantial balance of payments financing
from the IMF and project loans from the World Bank.
But it will aggravate the fears of US businesses that they will be left even
further behind as Vietnam's potentially dynamic economy is opened up to the
outside world. US companies may at present open offices in Vietnam and
negotiate contracts for future deals, but may not yet carry out these
contracts.
On Thursday, Mr Clinton met representatives of the families of servicemen
missing in action, who have strongly opposed normalisation of relations with
Vietnam, and promised that any further steps would 'strictly depend on
further progress by the Vietnamese on the POW/MIA issue'.
The POW/MIA lobby is a potent voice in US politics, and remains convinced
that Vietnam has not been honest in accounting for missing US soldiers and
airmen.
The president's own position on the issue is particularly delicate because
of his avoidance of military service in Vietnam. He accompanied his
announcement yesterday with statements of support from 18 members of
Congress who did serve in the war, including Senator John McCain of Arizona,
who was taken prisoner by the Vietnamese, and Senator John Kerry of
Massachusetts, who last year headed a Senate task force investigating the
fate of the POW/MIAs.
Mr Clinton said he would send a high-level mission to Hanoi to press for
further progress on accounting for the POW/MIAs.
The US has been working towards a more normal relationship with Vietnam
along the lines of a 'road map' sketched out by former president George
Bush, which linked economic and diplomatic concessions from the US to
progress towards peace and free elections in neighbouring Cambodia, on which
Vietnam has more than fulfilled its side of the bargain, and on the
POW/MIAs.
The administration must now convince the families of missing US servicemen
that they are likely to obtain more answers from Vietnam by making further
concessions than by maintaining an obdurate embargo.
The European Commission yesterday said it was ready to open negotiations on
a trade and co-operation pact with Vietnam, boosting the Hanoi regime's
campaign to end its commercial isolation.
</TEXT>
