<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 93 / Ireland blocks EC aid package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE 12 European Community member states were early this morning at odds over
how to divide up the Ecu157bn (Pounds 121bn) structural aid and regional
development budget for 1994-99, with Ireland blocking an outline agreement
broadly accepted by its partners.
As each country tried to secure more EC funds, the larger member states also
launched an assault on the European Commission's right to decide how money
for the Community's industrially stricken regions is to be allocated.
Mr Willy Claes, foreign minister of Belgium, which this week took over the
EC presidency, said that 'either we reach a timely decision, or we betray
our jobless and break the promises of Edinburgh', where EC heads of
government decided on the development package last December.
Ireland and the Netherlands threatened to veto any agreement on disbursing
the largest amount of development aid in EC history unless they received
guarantees on the share they want. At 3.30am, the Irish government decided
to block a deal because it had been offered IPounds 7.5bn, against the
IPounds 8bn prime minister Albert Reynolds insists he was promised at
Edinburgh.
Germany, Italy and the four poorest member states - Spain, Portugal, Greece
and Ireland - had earlier insisted that the eligibility threshold for
Objective 1, which includes the most deprived regions, be held at 75 per
cent of average per capita EC income.
These regions will get Ecu96.3bn, plus the Ecu15.5bn Cohesion Fund, which is
for the four poorest countries, on the most flexible terms reserved for the
Community's most backward areas.
The Commission wants Objective 1 status for Merseyside and the Scottish
Highlands and Islands, in the UK, Hainault in southern Belgium, and
Cantabria in northern Spain, even though they are above the 75 per cent
limit. Fierce negotiations early this morning looked certain to add to this
list. The French area of Valenciennes and Sambre-Avesnois adjoining Hainault
 -even though it is not a region - Argyll, Bute and West Moray in Scotland,
the Spanish Canary Islands and the Portugal and Madeira and the Azores are
the new beneficiaries.
This will almost certainly be approved, to preserve a 1988 political deal
making Northern Ireland and Corsica eligible for the most generous funding.
Since then, Corsica has effectively set a new eligibility benchmark, by
raising its per capita income to 79 per cent of the EC average. The areas
proposed by the Commission are just inside this.
Germany, France and the UK were seeking to deny the Commission the right to
decide on 'Objective 2' areas - those regions in industrial decline. In
addition, the UK was blocking Brussels' plans to spend part of the package's
money for training the unemployed or retraining workers who are in danger of
losing jobs because of industrial restructuring.
UK regions join EC's poorest, Page 5
</TEXT>
