<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 93 / Greater advocacy rights rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LORD Chancellor's advisory committee yesterday rejected the Law
Society's latest application for extended advocacy rights for solicitors. It
said additional safeguards were needed before solicitors employed in
commerce and industry, government and the Crown Prosecution Service could be
allowed in the higher courts.
The committee, chaired by Lord Griffiths, a law lord, has advised Lord
Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, that there are no objections to solicitors in
private practice being allowed to appear in the higher courts. But changes
are needed to the 1990 Courts and Legal Services Act before lawyers working
for the CPS and the Government Legal Service are given wider audience
rights.
The committee said there needed to be a limit on the amount of work CPS
lawyers were allowed to do in the Crown Court. The Law Society's application
would allow the CPS and the GLS to do all their higher court advocacy
in-house. The committee said that was unacceptable.
</TEXT>
