FT  03 JUL 93 / Pakistan's army gives Sharif an ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISLAMABAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PAKISTAN'S army, which has ruled the country for much of its 45-year
history, has told Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to resolve his deadlock with
the country's president or call fresh elections, Reuter reports from
Islamabad.
One minister said army chief Gen Abdul Waheed had given Mr Sharif two weeks
in which to end the crisis or call elections.
Diplomats and political analysts said that if Mr Sharif did not comply, Gen
Waheed could ask the president to dissolve parliament. Gen Waheed has
shuttled between Mr Sharif and President Ishaq Khan five times in a week to
try to persuade the other two members of the powerful troika that rules
Pakistan to end their confrontation, which has paralysed the administration
for months. Gen Waheed's latest meeting with the prime minister followed a
conference of corps commanders at army headquarters in Rawalpindi.
